              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/29613372/" class="">The Jewish Question</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/28748505/" class=" " title="Iris">Iris</a>
                (越是一个人，越要像模像样地生活)
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="29613372">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">The Jewish question, which to Bruno and most other theorists during the 1940s is a mere theological question mainly manifesting itself as the conflict between Christianity and Judaism that can be finally resolved by means of abolishment of religion privilege and political emancipation, to Marx, is deeply associated with social reality, especially with the inner structure of civil society and the v...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2013-12-04 05:05</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                The Jewish question, which to Bruno and most other theorists during the 1940s is a mere theological question mainly manifesting itself as the conflict between Christianity and Judaism that can be finally resolved by means of abolishment of religion privilege and political emancipation, to Marx, is deeply associated with social reality, especially with the inner structure of civil society and the very nature of capitalism. The political emancipation is not the final resolution to the question, and Jews can never be emancipated until the alienation between private person and public person, between individual life and species-life, between man and citizen be diminished and the whole human species be emancipated.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Marx’s discussion in On the Jewish Question can be divided into two parts: the criticism of politics started from a refutation and a detailed inquiry on Bruno’s idea of emancipation and then pushed the theological focus of discussion into the realm of politics; and the criticism of economics which also referred by Marx as Judaism mainly probed into problems of civil society and ended with investigation on problems of secular egocentric people. According to Marx, quite different from Bruno, the coexistence of religion and state was entirely possible. Religion in states with completed political emancipation was nothing more than a “manifestation of secular narrowness” (Reader, p31). However, the political emancipation of state was not likely result in the emancipation of man, “…the state can liberate itself from a constraint without man himself being really liberated; that a state may be a free state without man himself being a free man.” (Reader, p32) Though religion was banished to the domain of private affairs, political emancipation, instead of realizing emancipation of human species, rather aggravated it. States declared to abolish all the differences actually presupposed them. The cherished values such as rights of man, equality and freedom were in effect nothing but appearance. In these States, religion became “the essence of differentiation” (Reader, p35) which resulted from the division of state and civil society. Men therefore, as well had a double existence: “communal being” which “lives in the political community” and “private individual”, “treats other men as means, degrades himself to the role of mere means, and becomes the plaything of alien powers”.(Reader, p34) <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>It was the analysis of the nature of men under the capitalist system did Marx intrigue my huge interest. According to him, there existed a distinction between “man” and “citizen”. The spirits of capitalism such as freedom, security and equality actually were the guardians of men’s self-interests. In other words, “man” becomes the ultimate goal while “citizen” was reduced to means. “It is man as bourgeois and not man as a citizen who is considered the true and authentic man.” (Reader, p43) What is the characteristic of this “man” then? They are isolated individuals, indifferent to each other. Egoism is their best description. The only thing that can bound them together is their interests. Money is their god, and huckstering is their worldly cult. “It…has left remaining no other nexus between man and man than naked self-interest, than callous ‘cash payment’. It has drowned the most heavenly ecstasies…in the icy water of egotistical calculation. It has resolved personal worth into exchange value, and in place of the numberless indefeasible chartered freedoms, has set up that single, unconscionable freedom-Free trade. In one word, for exploitation, veiled by religious and political illusions, it has substituted naked, shameless, direct, brutal exploitation.” (Manifesto of the Communist Party, Reader, p475)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>By clarifying these two dimensions of life, Marx intended to reveal the hypocrisy nature of capitalism and successfully translated the Jewish question into the enterprise of emancipation the whole human species. He concluded that only by combining these two dimensions together, returning individual man to species-being, can human emancipation be fully completed.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Questions:<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1.	How will Marx view charity activities if he regard the nature of man under capitalist system as egocentric?<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2.	Comparing with the United States, the strongest capitalist country, China, as the biggest socialist country, the development of philanthropy there is actually faced with more difficulties and restrictions. Comparing with American millionaires’ enthusiasm towards charity activities, Chinese millionaires obviously are more inclined to choose a luxury life than do charities. There is also a tendency among Chinese people not to help others because they don’t want to get themselves in trouble. How will Marx explain this?

                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







